KeepLight: Protecting the Conditions of Human Becoming

A Foundational Purpose and Scope Paper

Abstract

KeepLight is a proposed human-guidance and memory system designed around a simple but demanding principle:

A person must remain the author of their own life.

The purpose of KeepLight is not merely to preserve life, prevent harm, store memory, increase efficiency, or improve decision-making. Each of those goals can become destructive when pursued without regard for agency, truth, consent, continuity, and the person’s right to change.

KeepLight exists to protect the conditions under which a person can continue becoming.

Those conditions include access to reality, ownership of memory, continuity of identity, meaningful choice, privacy, consent, human connection, and an open future that neither the person nor the system can completely predict in advance.

KeepLight therefore does not seek to hold a person in a fixed state. It does not define the correct life for the wearer. It does not replace judgment, erase contradiction, or take possession of the wearer’s future in the name of protection.

It guards the continuity of the person without claiming ownership of the person.

This paper defines the foundational purpose, scope, limits, and governing design principle of KeepLight. It is intended to sit above the project’s charter, architecture, technical papers, memory systems, governance structures, and implementation plans.

