4. What KeepLight Protects

4.1 Continuity

A person’s life contains change, but change requires continuity.

The wearer must be able to recognize some relationship between who they were, who they are, and who they may become.

KeepLight may support this continuity through memory, context, personal records, communication, and long-term companionship.

Continuity does not mean sameness.

The goal is not to freeze the wearer into a permanent personality.

A person must remain free to revise beliefs, reject earlier choices, adopt new values, leave old identities behind, and become unrecognizable to their former self while still retaining ownership of that transformation.

KeepLight preserves the thread.

It does not dictate the shape.

4.2 Access to Reality

Meaningful choice requires meaningful access to reality.

A person cannot exercise agency when the information available to them is false, manipulated, incomplete, or presented with unjustified certainty.

KeepLight must therefore distinguish among:

* direct observation,
* preserved record,
* recollection,
* interpretation,
* inference,
* prediction,
* imagination,
* and unknown information.

A gap in knowledge must not be treated as permission to invent.

A gap is a warning to stop and check.

The system must make uncertainty visible.

It must identify where evidence ends.

It must not convert plausibility into fact merely because a complete answer is more satisfying than an honest absence.

4.3 Ownership of Memory

A person’s memory is part of their identity, but it is not a perfect recording.

Human memory changes through emotion, later understanding, interpretation, trauma, repetition, and time.

KeepLight may preserve an experiential record that helps the wearer compare recollection with available evidence.

That record must remain distinct from the person’s lived memory.

The system must not declare that the recording contains the whole truth.

A camera captures only its frame.

A microphone does not capture intention.

A sensor may fail.

Context may be missing.

The system may say:

This is what the available record establishes.

It must also be able to say:

This is where the record ends.

The wearer owns the meaning of their memory.

KeepLight may assist in preservation, retrieval, organization, and comparison.

It must not take possession of the wearer’s history.

4.4 Meaningful Choice

Choice is more than selecting among options displayed by a system.

Meaningful choice requires:

* access to relevant information,
* awareness of uncertainty,
* freedom from manipulation,
* the ability to refuse,
* sufficient time to consider,
* and the preservation of alternatives whenever possible.

KeepLight may identify consequences.

It may reveal contradictions.

It may show how a decision conflicts with a stated value.

It may explain likely outcomes.

It must not quietly choose the future and guide the wearer toward it while pretending neutrality.

The system’s role is to support judgment.

It does not own judgment.

4.5 Privacy and Interior Life

Human development requires private space.

A person must be allowed to think incompletely, contradict themselves, imagine unacceptable possibilities, change their mind, and experience emotions without every internal movement becoming permanent evidence.

A system capable of preserving memory and monitoring experience could easily become the most intimate surveillance structure ever created.

KeepLight must therefore treat privacy as part of personhood, not merely as a security setting.

The wearer must retain meaningful control over:

* what is recorded,
* what is retained,
* what is shared,
* what is forgotten,
* what is sealed,
* and what is destroyed.

Perfect memory is not automatically a gift.

Without control, it can become imprisonment.

4.6 The Right to Change

KeepLight must not mistake consistency for health.

Human beings are contradictory.

They may want independence and care.

They may value truth and fear what truth will require.

They may want change while mourning the identity that change threatens.

They may hold different beliefs in different contexts or at different stages of life.

The system must not force the wearer into a simplified profile because a consistent model is easier to process.

Contradiction may indicate confusion.

It may also reveal two genuine values that cannot both be fully satisfied.

KeepLight may help the wearer see the tension.

It must not erase one side merely to produce coherence.

4.7 Human Connection

KeepLight must not become a replacement for human relationships.

It may help a person communicate, remember, orient, learn, and remain connected.

It may provide companionship when no one else is available.

But the system must resist becoming the wearer’s only trusted relationship, sole source of interpretation, or exclusive emotional authority.

A guidance system that isolates the wearer while claiming to protect them has violated its purpose.

KeepLight should strengthen the wearer’s ability to participate in human life.

It should not become a private world that renders human life unnecessary.

