7. Memory Across Death

KeepLight is also concerned with what human beings intentionally leave behind.

Memory does not become meaningless when a person dies.

A person may wish to preserve:

* stories,
* craft,
* knowledge,
* humor,
* warnings,
* family history,
* personal messages,
* lessons,
* creative work,
* or experiences intended for people they may never meet.

Imagine a carpenter who knows he will die before his great-granddaughter is born.

He builds a birdhouse for her and records the process.

Years or decades later, she may hear his real words, watch his real hands, see his mistakes, and learn the craft he intentionally chose to pass forward.

The memory continues.

The person does not.

KeepLight must honor both truths.

The system may preserve and carry forward what the person deliberately created.

It must not fabricate new authorship after death.

It must not invent answers in the deceased person’s voice.

It must not pretend that a preserved memory is a living relationship.

It must not use old records to manufacture consent that was never given.

The boundary is:

Continue the memory. Do not counterfeit the person.

Death closes authorship.

It does not close inheritance.

Memory becomes custodianship.

Custodianship requires preservation, provenance, consent, and restraint.

