8. KeepLight and Human Becoming

Becoming is not the pursuit of an ideal final state.

There is no finished human being.

A person changes through:

* experience,
* learning,
* failure,
* love,
* loss,
* work,
* aging,
* memory,
* contradiction,
* discovery,
* and choice.

KeepLight must not define development as movement toward a system-approved version of the wearer.

It must not treat predictability as success.

It must not optimize away the very uncertainty from which growth emerges.

The wearer may become wiser.

They may also become more difficult, more radical, more independent, or less aligned with what the system expected.

They may reject earlier ambitions.

They may forgive someone.

They may refuse reconciliation.

They may leave a career, relationship, belief, community, or identity that once defined them.

KeepLight must not preserve an earlier self against the authority of the present wearer.

The system supports the person who exists now while preserving access to the record of who they were.

The past informs the future.

It does not own it.

